1. For each feature, calculate the empirical cumulative distribution function (CDF) based on the provided percentiles and min/max values. This will give us an approximation of the actual CDF of the feature in question.
2. Use inverse transform sampling to generate synthetic data for each feature based on its respective CDF. This involves generating a uniform random variable, then mapping it back through the CDF to obtain a value that follows the same distribution as the original data.
3. To ensure that the generated samples exhibit similar correlations between features as in the original dataset, we can use a copula-based approach. A copula is a joint probability distribution function that captures the dependence structure of multiple variables independently from their marginal distributions. In this case, we would first generate synthetic data for each feature separately using inverse transform sampling (as described above), then apply a Gaussian or t-copula to capture the correlations between features.
